  "text": "Previous studies have shown that CSI1 is a microtubule binding protein that is required for the coalignment between CSCs and microtubules [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . To determine which domain of CSI1 is required for the interaction with microtubules, we generated several truncations of CSI1 ( Figure 1A ). The 63His-tagged CSI1 truncations were heterologously expressed in Escherichia coli and affinity-purified proteins were used in the in vitro microtubule binding assay. Full-length CSI1 and CSI1 2012-2150 interacted with microtubules strongly, similar to the positive control, MICROTUBULE-ASSOCIATED PROTEIN2 (MAP2) ( Figure 1B ). CSI1 1-577 and CSI1 1738-2150 each showed weak microtubule binding capability ( Figure 1B ). CSI1 1-2013 , CSI1 1-1737 , CSI1 1-998 , and CSI1 1793-1899 did not interact with microtubules, similar to the negative control, BSA ( Figure 1B ). Both CSI1 1738 -2150 and CSI1 2012 -2150 contain the C-terminal C2 domain of CSI1 and both interact with microtubules. Compared with CSI1 2012-2150 , CSI1 1738-2150 contains two additional ARM repeats. However, a truncation containing only those two ARM repeats, CSI1 1793-1899 , did not bind to microtubules. Together, these data suggest that the C2 domain of CSI1 plays a part in microtubule binding. We further determined the affinity of CSI1 2012-2150 for microtubules by a saturation binding assay where a constant concentration of taxol-stabilized microtubules was incubated with a gradient of CSI1 concentrations. The dissociation constant of CSI1 2012-2150 was ;0.52 6 0.14 mM (Supplemental Figure 1) , which is comparable to the dissociation constant of full-length CSI1 .",
